            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is hydrometer temperature correction?</h2>
              <p>
                A brewing hydrometer is calibrated to read correctly at a
                specific reference temperature, typically
                <strong>60°F (15.6°C)</strong> or <strong>68°F (20°C)</strong>.
                When you measure wort, beer, wine, or cider at a different
                temperature, the liquid’s density changes and the hydrometer
                reading is biased.
              </p>
              <p>
                Hydrometer temperature correction converts your
                <em>observed</em> specific gravity (SG) at the sample
                temperature into the SG it would have at the calibration
                temperature. This lets you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Compare readings taken on different brew days.</li>
                <li>
                  Calculate <strong>original gravity (OG)</strong>,
                  <strong>final gravity (FG)</strong>, and
                  <strong>ABV</strong> accurately.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use brewing software and style guidelines that assume
                  corrected SG values.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How this calculator works</h2>
              <p>This tool offers two correction modes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Accurate (polynomial)</strong> – uses a polynomial fit
                  to the temperature dependence of water density and typical
                  wort. This is similar in spirit to the ASBC tables and many
                  professional brewing calculators.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple (linear)</strong> – uses an easy-to-understand
                  linear approximation that is close enough for small
                  temperature differences.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Accurate mode (recommended)</h3>
              <p>
                In Accurate mode we compute a temperature factor based on the
                density of water at the sample and calibration temperatures. A
                commonly used approximation for the density of water (in g/mL)
                as a function of temperature in °C is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <code>
                  ρ(T) ≈ 1.00130346 − 0.000134722124·T − 0.00000204052596·T² −
                  0.00000000232820948·T³
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>We then scale the observed SG by the ratio of densities:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <code>
                  SG<sub>corrected</sub> = SG<sub>observed</sub> ×
                  [ρ(T<sub>sample</sub>) / ρ(T<sub>calibration</sub>)]
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                This captures the non‑linear change in water density with
                temperature and is accurate across typical brewing ranges.
              </p>

              <h3>Simple linear approximation</h3>
              <p>
                For a quick mental estimate, many brewers use a linear rule of
                thumb. For a hydrometer calibrated at 20°C:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <code>
                  ΔSG ≈ k × (T<sub>sample</sub> − T<sub>calibration</sub>)
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                where <code>k</code> is a small constant (on the order of
                0.00025–0.0003 SG per 5°C or 10°F).
              </p>
              <p>
                Our Simple mode uses a temperature‑dependent slope tuned so that
                it matches the Accurate mode at common brewing temperatures, but
                you should still prefer Accurate mode when precision matters.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for reliable hydrometer readings</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cool the sample when you can.</strong> Try to get
                  within ±5°F (±3°C) of the calibration temperature.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Degas the sample.</strong> Gently swirl or shake to
                  remove CO₂ bubbles that can stick to the hydrometer stem.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Read at eye level.</strong> Take the reading at the
                  bottom of the meniscus (the curved surface of the liquid).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check your hydrometer in distilled water.</strong> At
                  the calibration temperature, it should read 1.000. If not,
                  note the offset.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
